Subject The First Dream~
Text
After laying down, preparing for your sleep for the night, and falling
deep into a slumber, your mind goes at peace, and thoughts begin to gather
into a vision; at first, it was merely as though someone turned over a vial
filled with multiple colors of ink.  The scene swirls, slowly coming to the
form of a library, filled with bookshelves of mahagony stacked with a variety
of many books.  At the bottem of one of these bookshelves, far off in a courner
of the library, was a round, wooden table with one solitary chair and a single
candle lit at the center of it.  A man occupied the chair, dawned in the
red robes of a Conclavian, with long black hair and two black angels wings
sprouting from his back.  He was flipping through the pages of a book open
before him, leaning his head against his hand, which was proped up on the
table.  A dull emptiness filled his eyes, as he recited the names of many
spells to himself ("Acid blast...word of death...storm of vengeance...ect..)
Almost to the end of the book, a folded up loose sheet of paper falls to the
ground.  The person scoots his chair back and leans over to pick up the paper.
He examines it; it seems to be very old, yellow with years, but none of the
sterotypical cracks and crincles, as though it had been safeguarded from
most of time.  He unfolded the piece of paper, and began to dully read the
spidery contents.  His eyes stop at a spot, and he peers intently at it.  He
stands up and reachs for the center of the table, bringing the candle over
to him.  He then sits back down again, and re-reads what he had seen, and even
re-reads it a third time aloud, just to make sure he had the details right.
 
"...This spell, which mimics the death and rebirth of a Phoenix, is one of
the oldest og magics, used by desperate Magi.  Its prerequisits are out of
the norm; it may be difficult for some, yet easy for others.  This spell
requires a lightfollower, female in nature.  Without physical or magical force
must the lightfollower strip her clothing, as part of her particiaption in
the spell.  Then, by reciting the words below, and with the simple means of
a touch to the lightfollower's bare stomach, the caster may incase a rebirth
of himself within the lightfollower.  More times then not, the caster meets
his or her death immediatly afterwords, though there are cases of more power-
ful Magi escaping the bad fortures of the spell.  Reguardless of escape or not,
the caster immediatly dies upon the birth of his or her rebirthed form.  When
reborn, it is often that the caster may come to look somewhat as the light-
follower that he or she incased themselves into.  The gestation period is
often known to proceed three fold faster then normal, and the effects of the
conception are astounding; even after the lightbringer's death, the rebirth
would still proceed.  The caster has been known to be reborn even if the host's
body were burned to ashes.  The very powers of this spell draw energies not
unlike a Phoenix's, so to some scholars, it is not surprising that this is
so.  Many even go so far as to call this spell, "A second chance to life..."
 
The man reads this passage over and over again.  Each time he does, his eyes
glow brighter, as if though hopeful of something.  His face then goes pale, as
if though his stomach was doing somersaults, and he folds the paper back up
and stuffs it back into the book.  He moves to the bookshelf and stuffs the
book back in its place.  He blows the candle out, pushes in the chair, and
begins to make his way out of the library.  However, he stops at the door,
his hand keeping hold of the handle.  The soft pitter-patter of rain can be
heard on the windows, and extremely dim bits of sunlight escape into the
library, giving an eerie setting to it all.  The man turns his gaze back to
the table, with its candle still letting up small wisps of smoke.  He looks to
the general area where the book had been placed, and looks at it almost long-
ingly.  His breathing becomes labored, as he was clearly rooted to the spot.
He closes his eyes tightly, and as he does, the image slowly begins to fade
away into darkness, blotching up like a painted picture in the rain.  The last
visible thing is the man's hand, which remains where it is for the longest
time.  Finally, the hand lets go of the door handle, and the last bits of the
image fade into blackness...
~
