As soon as Cordani can, he brings himself to his feet and looks to the two dead guards with sympathy.  Two innocent lives ruined, if not lost because of his rage.  He starts cursing himself, beating himself up in his mind at his actions.  A true knight would never let their anger overcome them, a true knight would never strike like a coward as he has.  But still a part of him seems to agree and tries to reason, as if what happened was more of a saving act rather then one of a madman. 
At least he didn't step over the edge--lose his mind completely--who knows when he would've stopped if that had happened.
He quickly turns to the only place where he could take solace; the Last Call.
Cordani steps into the bar right as the barkeeper rings the brass bell, clocking the hour.  He starts unstrapping his armor well before he's halfway to the corner table he often dwells at; the same table his father before him sat at each night.  A lady notices the wounds and his condition, launches to her feet to assist him.
"Are you all right?" she asks, offering him a hand.
"Yes I am," Cordani replies.  He pauses to bow his head and properly thank her for her time before dismissing the fact that he need's any help.  She sighs exasperatedly before sinking back in her seat. 
"I told ya, he's a darn knight--They hold their pride over their very lives, Mary!" Her partner remarks as she takes a quick whisk from his tankard that he futile tries to keep from her.
"At least unlike you they something if anything..." she replies snidely then turns her gaze to Cordani, "...honor."
Cordani lets his head fall and quickly wipes a tear that managed to escape his tightly shut eyes.  In the eyes of others it may look like he just came from a reputable battle, but he knows the truth and it bores down on his soul.  He has no honor, and years shall pass as he tries to gain some honor, and some respect for himself, from himself.
 
(((END OF CHAPTER ONE)))
