Subject If anything, a legacy - (1/2) - II~
Text
Days pass and I stay nights in an alley.  I try to tell myself it is punishment for the evil I continue to do, but I know better, I know it's because I don't want to find a place and I don't have the steel nor copper to afford a night even if I could find one.  The rain isn't letting up and I couldn't help but know it's no good for my armor.  I tap my javelin and shake my head trying to force myself asleep.  At least in my dreams all I see is black, all I hear is nothing, that's all I want.
 
The sun comes up and I feel it blanket me in warmth.  This is probably what it feels like to own a home, some land, something to look forward to.  I smile because for the moment I think I'm happy.  I don't believe I truly know what it means, but my soul feels alive until the darkness comes over me again.  My smile fades and my fists clench, revealing to me the pain my body suffered yesterday.  I let my eyes open and I take my time to get accustomed to the light.
My javelin acts as a hand as I place it firmly on the ground to lift myself up.  Taking in a deep breath I try to feel good again, but it's gone, the feeling's gone.  As I fully wake up I notice a figure's been standing not two meters away.  I look upon him and notice he's alone, is probably my height and maybe weighs twenty stones more.  His facial emotion is that of a controlled anger, something I'm very much used to.
"Is there something happening around me that I don't know?" I ask, my right hand feels the javelin it holds as if assuring it is there.
"Someone told me it was you," he says, "it was you that killed my brother!  He may have been a young and eager guard, but I have to know... was it you?"
I sigh exasperatedly and shake my head in doubt, hoping I could say no and that it would be truthful.
"If he was one of the two that lay dead on Bough street then it was I.  You can go get the rest of the guards, I will not flee," I answer.  I consider going to jail, or even getting killed here as punishment.  Anything would probably be better then living with the dark torment that I suffer everyday. 
"It was you... it was you," the man repeats, considering what to do with the answer.  He unsheathes his blade, a steel broadsword, and narrows his eyes with hatred.  "I will not take this to the city, I will handle it myself!  Take your weapon to arms bastard, so that I may avenge my brothers death!"
My javelin radiates with electricity and I feel compelled to fight him, the darkness, the urge.  I cannot succumb to it again, already.  I turn my head and drop my weapon.
"If you want to kill me, go ahead."
"I will not strike you before you're ready, pick up your weapon!" he demands, gripping his sword's hilt even tighter.  I drop my shield and snatch my javelin with both hands, lunging forward.  I try to tell myself I'll go easy and let myself lose, but I can feel my anger and I can feel the tension in my arms.  Our weapons collide and he strategically falls to his knee and swings his blade, angled upward, toward my gut.
 I push myself backward with both my feet, but the sword slices through my breastplate and grazes me.  I quickly check myself then glance at his sword, it looks as if he came prepared as it's edge looks sharp enough to slice a thread of hair.  I thrust my javelin forward to no particular area and he quickly deflects, grabs my arm with his elbows and twists it so that my javelin slips from my hands and lands on the ground. 
I try to recover but I cannot think fast enough and am quickly on the ground.  The sword comes down and grazes my cheek, the pain forcing my eyes tightly shut.
"Pick up your weapon," the man orders.  I slowly open my eyes to see, to see that I'm still alive.  The tip of the sword is rested on my face.  I quickly snatch my javelin and then get booted in the side.  "Get up and get out of here!  I don't want to see scum like you in this city, again!" He threatens before sheathing his blade and taking his leave.
I gather myself up and feel the scar left on my face.  It burns, worse then normal.  I feel the entire side of my face going numb, as if my life was slowly being sucked from the wound.  I latch my javelin to the back of my breastplate and stagger out of the alley, praying for Chemosh to take my soul, yet at the same time yearning for the forgiveness of Mishakal.
<*>
It has been some time--several months I believe--that I've visited the port city of Port O Call.  As I walk down the street I pass civilians and other travelers.  They glance upon me and smile or nod their heads, something about a knight's presence makes them feel safer.  I cannot return a smile nor a nod as my sins cannot be accounted for nor forgotten with such gestures.
Every time I pass a city guard--whether they be on duty or going home--my hands twitch and I nervously grasp at my javelin to make sure it's there.  I don't do it in thought, but my body knows I'm scared.
I feel my skin tingle and the invisible eyes bore down upon me.  But it doesn't matter, as long as those visions don't come back.  Curse that mage!  What was his name?  Talwin, yes, that is it!  Him and his stupid gem, what has it done to me?  That memory it showed, it wasn't mine--was it?  Those people that were slaughtered, was that from my anger and rage?  I can't remember anything from before the darkness encompassed me in Palanthas. 
 
(((First 1/2 of the chapter.  To be continued...)))
