Subject If anything, a legacy - (2/2) - II~
Text
(((..continued)))
Is my name really Cordani?  Or is that just a memory?  Damn, even as I am I wasn't this angry.  If that mage didn't cast those magick's on me, or whatever he did that made me get this memory--the same memory replays over and over and every time I see it clearer and clearer.  The worse thing though, that person in the visions, the one I feel is me... he's dead.
 
*THUD!*
I bump into a lady by accident.  Her sack falls and it's contents fall out.  I bring myself back to reality and I quickly move to gather what dropped at my fault.  She seems stunned, as if she also was in thought when we collided.  I give her back her snack and brush a head of spinach off before putting it back atop her belongings. 
"Thank you, sir knight," she says, beaming a heartfelt smile as if it were her fault.
"No need to thank me ma'am, it was my mistake and I owe you an apology," I answer with a brisk shake of my head.  That's when I notice she has two a backpack and another sack burdening her down.  I think I can help and although know it's far from what I must do for redemption, at least it's something.
"You seem to be burdened down a might, would you care for a hand?" I offer.  She weakly smiles and starts to decline but I have nothing of it, quickly removing the sack from her shoulder and hoisting it on mine.
"Where do you live?"
 
Once we arrive to her place of residence I keep my distance and allow her to make known of my company.  At first it seems as if the owner was thankful until he gets a better look at me.  I know he looks familiar, the scorn on his face further strengthens that presumption.  He snatches the sack out of my hand and pulls the lady in--she's most obviously his sister.
"Have I done something wrong?" I inquire, sheathing my sword as I had brought it out to salute the family before I was either welcomed or dismissed.  He quickly reaches in the house and then steps out, closing the door.  The look on his face, his eyes, it is then when I remember seeing him before.  In the alley, the guard's brother. 
"I'm sorry," I apologize and quickly turn away to leave.
"Stay your ground!" He demands.  My hand moves from my sword to the javelin latched on the back of my breastplate.  I pray he doesn't wish to fight me, it will only satisfy the darkness watching over me and enrage the anger that I do my hardest to keep calm.
"I-I don't wish to fight you," I say, turning around to face him.  Though those are my words, I know I feel otherwise.  He can see it, he can see that something inside me wishes to unleash itself and bring down the wrath of the heavens on him.  But that is not what I really want, it is just something I really cannot comprehend nor control right now.
"You killed my brother and now you're here to torment me and my family?  I let you live, hath I made a mistake?"
I do not answer, I cannot answer.  I am no true knight yet I try to make myself believe I am bound to some code of honor.  I wish to explain myself, but I deem not to.  I just look him in the eye and hope he would act accordingly to what he is bound to as a knight.
As time slips by I notice his grip on his sword loosen, he shakes his head and turns away--no scowl, no warning, not even an acknowledgment.  I sigh, pivot on my heel and make my way back to the city.  Has he forgiven me?  I cannot even forgive myself yet I am walking away in one piece.  Or is it the Gods are shunning down on me, forcing me to suffer.  But I can take my own life, can't I?  Is that my destiny?
As I walk in thought the vision comes back, the pain wreaks through my veins.  I gasp for breath but soon all I can see is darkness, all I can feel is cold.  I see a sword rise, a blackened sword with runes of such that pain my heart.  I feel a rage inside me that I cannot even comprehend.  The mage Talwin is there in my visions, I feel as if I know him.  I know my name, it's Cordani--but not Cordani Threshold?
There are others I can feel, there are memories that are not my own.  Skeletons charge pass me and I shiver in mind, but in this vision, I know them!  They are my men, aren't they?  Chemosh, I feel the power of Chemosh in me.  It is then I realize that in this vision--in this truth--I am dead.
As sudden as it happens it is over.  It is night and my stomach growls for some indulgence.  I look around and feel cold--as if I am still dead--but soon the warmth comes back to me and I realize where I am.
Is what I see what I am, what I used to be, or what I am to become?  And if it is so, if any, how did that mage trigger such?  And with this knowledge, will I still falter to the path in which is before me?
I close my eyes and take in a deep breath. It is not the Gods I seek forgiveness from--it is not even myself--it is the countless souls of mortal men of which I have brought suffering to.  As I have dedicated myself before--though then I did not have much a guidance as I do now--I shall dedicate myself again to challenge the heavens and step forth in the faith of the mortals to shed the light on those blinded by the Gods they follow.
My burden shall weigh me down to the abyss but I shall lift others up so that my sins will be redeemed in their eyes.
 
(((END OF CHAPTER TWO)))
-Cordani Threshold
