Subject If anything, a legacy - (1/1) - III~
Text
I sit in last call, drowning my sorrows with a tankard of ale.  I keep my eyes closed as I replay the events that took place behind these walls not but a week ago.  My feet impatiently tap the wooden floor and I try to keep my breathing calm, as even in thought the visions tear at my soul.
The mage Talwin and his cursed ruby unleashed upon me what not even I can explain.  I was there but I could only watch as something, whatever it was, over powered my body and mind.  I felt the uneasiness of the darkness-the slithering inside my veins-the blood upon my skin.  I couldn't control the rage, though I felt as if whatever possessed me had complete control over it.
After a while I didn't fight it--I don't know if it was the power or the complete assurance the presence had, but I liked it.  I saw my aspirations come true while the darkness embraced me.  The power I had within me I knew I would be able to challenge the Gods without the long toil that currently lay ahead.  But I also know I cannot trust that power as it held no feelings toward those I care for and it disregarded what I try to uphold in myself in being a knight.
Even now as I drown myself with aleI can feel the dark presence inside of me, and I also feel as if those dark orbs that are watching me in wait are satisfied.
I shake my head and push up from my table.  The power is tempting, but how can I give up what I've been so hard at trying to build up?  My honor.
I remember my talk with Darkahn and how most, if not all of the mortals with the immediate power to step up to the Gods do not.
But if I give up my honor then what will hold me from giving into the darkness and temptations when I do challenge the Gods?  What will hold me to my original goals?  But if I wait, how long will it take before the flame burns out?
My head is lowered as I leave the bar.  I trod down Bough street and take some time to go over my thoughts.  Is the darkness worth the time it will take for me to achieve the power naturally?  But even if it isn't, will I ever be able to achieve such power in life?
My thoughts are interrupted as I come upon a brawl between two rowdies.  A man never interrupts another man's fight, I tell myself, but still my hand nervously grips and unlatches my javelin.
"Hey!  What is going on here?" A guard yells out, rushing over to the scene.  I glance at the men who quickly separate as the guard approaches with his mace in hand.  They mutter something to each other and then quickly greet the guard.  I just stand there, wondering what's going on.  Fingers point.  The guard sends a fierce glare to me.  This is why I should've kept walking.
"Wait," I try to explain, but my arm is quickly grabbed as the guard attempts to thrust me against a wall.  I stand my ground and extend my other leg for better resistance.  "I had nothing to do with this!"
He quickly opens his mouth to speak but as quickly falls to the ground, yelping in pain.  One of the men struck a sharp dagger in his back and the other stands there with his large, muscular arms crossed.
"Get out of here, boy!"  They warn me.  My eyes widen at the act and the grip on my weapon tightens.  "What, you here for a fight as well?"
I easily defend against the smaller man with the dagger, though he tries futilely to harm me with his cheap attacks.  But the larger man, the warrior, manages to bring me down in not even four blows.
As they leave and I lie, hanging desperately onto life, I realize that no matter how much longer I train I never will be able to stand up to the Gods, not as the cursed knight, the weak mortal, that I am.  And I also realize how foolish I would be if I expect to depend upon one with the attunement to the magicks to stand aside me, or for me.  The mortal men need leaders, but ones with as powerful a step as a vision.
'Take my soul so that I may embrace the darkness,' I pray, tears stroll down my eyes.  There is nothing I have to lose in embracing the darkness, the rage.  There is none in all of Ansalon who would shed a tear for the life of just another mortal in his passing day.  At least with the power the darkness, the death has to offer, I will be able to stand before the Gods on my own.  For no mortal will follow me unless they see afore that I possess the strength to challenge the Gods, and that, I do.
 
(((END OF CHAPTER THREE)))
-Cordani Threshold, Deathknight?
