Text
The Gods WILL give way to those that are rightly entitled to all of Ansalon!  All dwarves, elves, kender, human, every race, every kin, we of mortal men shall stand our ground and take claim to what is ours.
But that will come in time, for there always has to be the one who steps first into the waters before the rest are brave enough to stand for themselves.  I am Cordani, and if anything, I will go down leaving behind a legacy for the sons of mortals to learn upon.
 
It is just another day for most people, but not for me.  I watch as the sun slowly sets, and I know it is time for me to take action.  With my loyal steed I gallivant through Solanthus in search for a lone dragonarmy officer.  The air gets cooler and the smell of rations growing stronger, but that does not stay my mind for very long as I quickly spot what I'm looking for.
This when my journey shall begin, and it shall not end until either I die, or the Gods give way.
There, adorned in his blood streaked armor and walking in full stride with his large and bloodied axe in hand is the dragonarmy officer I am looking for.  His eyes are that of a determined, yet weakened mortal.  I shake my head and tell myself it is for a better cause.  Those words reach my lips and he looks my way.  I think about reconsidering, or at least that's what I mask my fear as telling myself, but I know that I'm fighting for a cause, so I know I will win.
"For the future!" I quietly cry out, gripping my sword tightly as I rush him.  He brings his axe up to defend and as the two connect a loud clang rattles the streets. I pray to finish the fight before it draws any attention.
The axe almost immediately afterward swings low and cleaves my left thigh, forcing that leg to back-step and my right foot to pivot forward.  I manage to take advantage of the situation and quickly end the fight, using the momentum to thrust my sword into the officer's neck.  
Blood trickles down the razor sharp blade of my sword and eventually meets with my gauntlets.
I waste no time and fall to my knees, ignoring the pain that jolts through my body, quickly stripping the officer of his suit.  I breath hard and sweat pours down my forehead and palms as I hide the body in an alley for none to find, knowing I will come back to finishing the job, cover my tracks.
Wiping the sweat from my forehead I take in a deep breath and then bundle the gear up and mount my steed. 
 
Before the High Clerist Tower, on the High Knight road, I watch as a Solamnic Knight patrols the grounds.  The sun is almost fully set and though the knight seems to be walking a bit farther then the regular patrol, he is still in quite visible range of the other guards.
I take in a deep breath and whisper into my horses ear, take a good few steps toward the Knight.  My heart is racing, the burden of my armor isn't helping either.
'Well-- forgive me, for this is working toward a better cause--' I speak, approaching the knight with my head hung down.  My hand is on the hilt of my sword, and I can feel the dry wind brush through the open cracks of my armor, chilling me even more so, twitching my nerves.
'What are you talking about, sir?' The knight proudly asks, unaware that this will be the last day he brandishes the tainted steel of the Knights of the Crown.
'I will attone for my sins afterwards.  I cannot explain it to you, it will only make things harder on myself; you will die today,' I declare, quickly reaching back to smack my horse with the blunt side of my sword.
The guard glances about for reassurance of the other guards but my steed gallops forth toward the tower, grabbing the attention of the nearby guards who quickly rush to restrain it.  The guards on the tower walls also peer down to the horse, wondering what idiot could've left it out there?
'I am sorry!' I finally apologize, my sword quickly swinging forth as I push off toward the knight.
The knight cannot unsheath his weapon before I plunge my sword into his breastplate, grazing his chest and slicing his ribcage.  But that only gives me a slight advantage as he moves with the momentum of my lunge, throwing us both to the ground.
I try to free my sword but he connects two powerful blows to my face, almost knocking me out cold.
As my eyes jolt open each time his fist hits I can see my own blood being shot from my nose, but even so, all my mind sees is the greater vision, what I am working toward.  I cannot let some Solamnic Knight stand in my way.
As he regains footing and is about to call for help I kick him with my right leg with such a force I break his leg.  He falls on my left leg, which is already sore from the last fight, forcing me to yelp in pain.  But right now pain is the least thing on my mind and through determination I recover quickly and unveil a dagger hidden in my hard ankle sheath.  The metal feels smooth as it practically glides in my hand, the cool hilt bringing a warm assurance of victory.
 
My steed comes galloping back as I whistle for it.  I hoist myself and the dead Solamnic knight on the saddle, then gallops toward Solanthus.  None of the guards caught a glimpse of what happened, forcing a wry and twisted smile to my face.
As we are clear from any unwanted witnesses I cease my horse and throw the dead knight to the ground.  I rest my sore body on a tree stump as I rummage through my belongings for some paper and ink.
 
