I sit there on the tree stump, letting my body settle down and my heart calm as well.  The wind blows by me and I can feel the hint of rain in the cool breeze.  I consider what to write, knowing the effect I want from this.  My horse walks up to me, as if searching for answers to what I have just done--or maybe that is just what I want, someone, something to arise for me explain myself.  And so I lighten the grip of my fist as I start inking the paper, and look to the horse to speak.
'How can we bring followers to our cause if there is no reason?  We need war!  With war, sorrow will be forced upon countless lives.  Pain, suffering,' I take in a deep breath, 'these are the things that make people think, really think, and actually make choices on how they're living and what they're doing.
'If I can spark a war between the two, then I will also spark the minds of the mortals who may be our only hope when I confront the Gods.  If they can think about why they are going to slaughter each other, for the interest of their God, then perhaps they will see what I see.  Through the lies that their Gods thrust upon them, through the torment and sorrow their Gods force them to suffer, and yet in return they still get nothing, not even proper respect or acknowledgment from their so-called Gods!' 
 
My steed turns his head away.  I understand, wisdom is something not for animals, which tempts me to think about the Draconian scum that may never be able to see beyond their foolish Gods.  But they are still mortals and one day I will have to accept them as I do the rest, though they may be the hardest to convince and also the race whose choices may be the fate of my campaign.
I finish writing the note and watch as the ink quickly dries.  I hear the faint noise of horse shoes and quick shove the note into the lifeless hand of the Solamnic Knight.  
After that I quickly walk over to my belongings and release the axe and dragonarmy suit that I brought with me.  Being much too large for me to wear I use my steed to help me saunter about, as if I were an actual dragonarmy officer.  One wouldn't be able to tell from a far distance that I am an imposter, but I do not expect to keep this up much longer; just an impression, that's all I need.
 
As I return to the city of Solanthus I take refuge near a local guard tower.  There I speculate interest of action towards the Solamnic Knights, hoping for the right passerby to overhear me.  It isn't long before they throw me out, but that is all right, Osiris can always use some company--and I'm dying for some jerk chicken.
 
