Subject Return to Palanthas~
Text
The lithe body dexstrously bounded through the trees of Vingaard with speed short of haste and just faster then pure glee. The myriad of colored feathers caught the light of his gleaming silver jewelry with each leap of his supple legs. Despite his appearence of reckless speed, not a sound was made aside from the woodland creatures calling out like sentries of the sylvan scenery.
The Kagonesti had been running as the sun first spread its life giving rays like so many fingers through the leaves, branchs and clouds, and it was not until both Lunitari and Solinari had risen and the bottom rim of the sun had disappeared below the horizon that he stopped near a stream to pray and refresh.
Removing the deerskin moccasins worn on his feet, the short loincloth used for propriety and his plethora of silver jewelry decorated with beads and the feathers of a thousand still living birds, the elf plunged headfirst into the frigid waters, gently scraping his chest and legs against the rocks of the riverbed.
Swimming submerged, the kagonesti silently prayed to Habbakuk for sustenance and, whether the Fisher King had heard or not, Sikandar saw through the fluid realm a large trout, dying slowly and painfully from the bite of some larger aquarian predator. With a swift grab and a prayer of gratitude to Habbakuk, Sikandar rose to the surface of the stream with the barely struggling fish in his left hand.
Pulling his sun-bronzed body that bore no traces of a tanline from the water, Sikandar walked slowly but gently to his trinkets and gently placed the fish on a log. He gathered firewood as he sang an old tribal song his mother had taught him and as the sun finally settled behind him, he had started a small fire and cooked his meal.
Satiated, Sikandar put on his deerskin and silver, plunged his head into the crystal stream and drank long and eagerly. Checking he had his daggers, he set off Eastward once more, his keen elven sight and deceptive kagonesti muscles carrying him swiftly towards Palanthas.
As he broke through the woods, the anxiety in his gut became tangible and he stopped to stare at the metropolis that was Palanthas. It had been some years since he had last left the cities behind to their own selfish and petty bickerings. Now he felt it time to return.. or rather the whispers of Habbakuk's children had convinced them it was a man in Palanthas who could help him find his sister.. if she still lived.
~
