Subject Old Friends and New Foes~
Text
The Palanthian guards had given him confused looks as he entered, but no attempt was made to stop him for questioning. Either things in the city had become more peaceful, or the Solamnics had more dangerous things to worry about. Sticking to the sidestreets and alleys, Sikandar wound his way towards the center of Palanthas - towards the Temple of Paladine.
Moments after his arrival he paused behind the corner of a buidling to wretch violently. The stench of the city was oppressive, the animals within little more then slaves or toys for their self-centered masters and the multitudes of souls seemed to have forgotten they had one. His stomach empty, Sikandar finished the mile or so to the city on uneasy legs, the hard, unyielding cobblestones providing little comfort for his weary legs.
The square before the Temple of Paladine was sparcely populated, and Sikandar took note of the population here compared to the rest of the city. As his gaze reached from face to face it fell definetly on that of a large man in blackened armor. At once he realized why much of the Palanthian citizenry avoided the temple.. it had once again become (or never ceased to be?) a favorite spot of the Knights of Takhisis. 
How the population of Solamnics tolerated their presence so easily Sikandar could not guess, but as he approached the temple avoiding the Knights gaze, Sikandar caught his notice and was confronted before moving on.
"{DYou must know that I am here with a message for the Palanthian citizenry, one of death{x" the knight thundered with his hand on his weapon.
Sikandar replied in his broken Common: "{bI am no citizen of this city.. citizen of NO city.. I am Kagonesti you lapdog of Takhisis{x" he regretted his words as he had said them, but common came from his mouth.. as if he had no choice of the words.
The knight glared down at Sikandar, his eyes gleaming behind his dark helm: "{DIt matters little, but I would have you leave now if as you claim is true and you are not of this ci{x-"
The knight was interrupted as the cry of an elf maiden came across the square: "{BSikandar! Sikandar it is I, Serpintina! Where have you been for so long?{x"
Though his face was covered, Sikandar could see the knight raise his eyebrow from behind his helm and chuckle slightly. "{DNot from here eh? Well that incorrigible flirt Serpintina seems to recognize you, SIKANDAR.{x"
The beautiful magi walked quickly up and almost instantly recognized the situation. By now a small audience was paying attention from the periphery and an heated exchange began that seamlessly broke into elven, and quickly after that, violence seemed imminent.
Serpintina was attacked and Sikandar rushed to her aid. The blessings of the Dark Goddess proved strong and both elves hit the cobblestones hard. The Kagonesti awoke some time later with figures standing above him. "It is just like Palanthas for an occurance such as this to merit no alarm and only mild amusement," Sikandar thought as he looked frantically for Serpintina's corpse. He found her, still breathing but barely, and feebly pulled her close to the fountain to awaken her.
As her eyes fluttered open, Serpintina looked around quickly and in alarm: "{BWhere did that bastard go!?{x" Sikandar cupped another handful of water into her mouth and smiled, then reached behind him and pulled out a small black money purse with the symbol of the Knights of Takhisis on it.
In elven Sikandar spoke: "{bHe is gone Lady, though not with everything he came here with.. or for.{x" The magi looked at him slightly then understood with a smile that warmed Sikandar like little in a city could. "{bIt would be better for them if in the future these squires of Takhisis would learn to check their pockets as well as the pulse of their victims.{x" 
He smiled and winked at Serpintina then helped her to her feet. "{bCome!{x" he said weakly through teeth clenched in pain, "{bDinner is on Takhisis{x!"
