|                                                            |
|   As we all can easily figure out, even with our modest    |
| intelligence, feudal laws and the political structure of   |
| of Solamnia has greatly changed over the ages. It is, in   |
| fact, proven.                                              |
|   We could define the "First Age" of Solamnia as the age   |
| under the Empire of Ergoth: Solamnia was a frontier land,  |
| too distant from the Imperial Palaces of Daltigoth to be   |
| well goverened. The various feudal lords complained about  |
| the heavy taxation which impared the growth of local       |
| economy and sometimes caused famine. The Imperial Prefects,|
| whose authority was was superior to that of the local land-|
| lords, were very rigid and admitted no delay in the payment|
  | of taxes. It wasn't rare that the feudal lords and their   |
| populations were unable to pay them. Failure to do so,     |
| however, caused the alienation of the feud, from which     |
| returned to the direct control of the Emperor.             |
|   Many fallen nobles united with their cousins who were    |
| still in control of their lands, and under the flag of     |
| Count Mytrandar, the eastermost counties rebelled to       |
| against the central power of Emperor Thenkalin III, whose  |
| dynasty took the throne after the death of the just Emporer|
| Quevalin XXv, last of the most revered Quevalin line. But, |
| in the year 1850, after many deaths and a cruel repression,|
| the Imperial authority was restored, and the five Counts   |
| were executed or killed in battle.                         |
|   After a few years, when the taxes had risen once more,   |
| the wrath of another revolt had been incurred as the pop-  |
| ulation was stricken by another famine. The reamining      |
| Counts of the East embraced this new revolt, called "the   |
  | Rose Rebellion," after the red rose of the blazon from the |
  | crest of Count DiCaela, who was the leader of the uprise.  |
| So generalized was the revolt, that after a few defeats,   |
| the Imperial Marshal, Grand-Duke Alyusandrus of Foghaven,  |
| deemed it necessary to order the elite troops of the       |
  | Imperial Guard into battle. These elite troops were led by |
| a young and talented commander, General Vinas Solamnus,    |
| third son of the House of Vinasserre.                      |
