|                                                            |
|   Solamnus was not a power-hungry man, and he had no heirs.|
| And it was after this revelation that he went on a pilgri- |
| mage, a Quest of Honour. He asked the Gods for wisdom and  |
| guidance, for he well knew that the shadow of violence and |
| misery would return to the land he had freed after he had  |
| lain to the eternal rest. And it was on this Quest that the|
| Gods spoke to him. They intructed him in the creation of a |
| Knightly Order, the Knights of Solamnia.                   |
|   After the Kings Quest of Honour, he returned home and    |
| gave life to three Knightly Orders. At the time, every     |
| ranking member within these new Orders (having been his    |;| long standing and loyal military officers) received the    |
| charge to be the feudal government of a territory. Each    |
| with it's own degree of importance. Simple villages were   |
| held by simple Noblemen or Patrices, groups of towns by    |
| Barons. And finally, the larger territories were held by   |
  | Counts, Marquises, and Dukes.                              |
|   Some of these dukedoms, which contained historical places|
| or key-point fortresses were held by Princes. These Princes|
| were always the greatest of Heroes from the War of the Ice |
| Tears, like the Lord of Justice, Lord Angus Markennin - the|
| first Prince of Thelgaard. It was by this process of infeu-|
| dation that the whole of Solamnia had been divided into the|
| Provinces of today. Each one governed by a King with       |
| with authority extended to "lesser" feudataries (the       |;| Princes, Dukes, Marquises, Counts and Barons). Every land- |
| lord, regardless of title, can have, as valvassors, Noble- |
| men of Patrice rank, who rule one or more little villages  |
| and one castle or keep.                                    |
|   After this impressive and grand-scale reform (henceforth |;| called "the Feudal Reform"), the Council of the Knighthood |
| was established. From that time forth, as the higher autho-|
| rity to which every landlord, even Kings, had to pay       |
| obedience, and his permanent head was "the Grand Master."  |
  |   The Grand Master of the Knights of Solamnia who, as Lord |
| of Knights, holds the supreme and permanent power (both    |;| militarily and civil) over all the Kingdoms and lesser     |
| feudal states. The Grand Master is elected by the Grand    |
| Council of the Knights of Solamnia, so the supreme author- |
| ity is not hereditary like any other political position.   |
| Futhermore, the Feudataries are not automatically elected. |
| Why? Simply because they must be a ranking Knight from one |
| of the Three Orders.                                       |
