Text
I had recently begun my travels to do my duty as the Knight of the Aesthetic Order, to seek and protect knowledge from those who would attempt to destroy it, when I came upon a library in a small town east of Solanthus. I had heard rumors that this town, known as Lemish, had become a foothold near to Palanthas for Takhisis.
When I arrived the rumors were confirmed, though this was not my focus on coming here. I had heard early in my travels of a library, ages old, deep below the city. When I arrived at where the entrance of the library was supposed to be, I found a group of goblins and what appeared to be a Knight of Takhisis unsheathing weapons in a group around an elderly man in a red robe typical of those that a librarian would wear.
I heard the Knight demand information of the Librarian, knowledge of an ancient sword dating back to before the cataclysm. The Librarian, as followers of Gilean are instructed to do, gave the information freely, however the Knight was displeased with the answer and ordered the goblins to attack. As was befitting of my station I rushed in to protect the Librarian, slaying the goblins and coming face to face with the knight. He turned and fled.
Having no quarrel with him, I did not follow, my mission was to protect the Librarian, not slay Knights. As a matter of curiosity, I asked the Librarian about the Sword the Knight had inquiried about. He told me it was called Balancekeeper, and that it was said to be blessed by Gilean himself. The wielder was charged with protecting the Aesthetic clan, and all who sought knowledge.
As it was growing late at this point, the Librarian led me down into the ancient library where, after perusing several volumes, I discovered more about the sword. Like the fact that the Legendary Guardian had a brother who also wielded a weapon blessed by Gilean. A "Lance of the Void" as it was called. In an old tattered book in a corner of an old bookcase I found a loose description of where the tomb of the Legendary Guardian was.
In fact, The tomb was at the back of this very library, concealed behind what is now a temple to Gilean, built to protect the sword. I made my way back to the temple, where I was greeted by another elderly Librarian. He told me that the two of them had been guarding the library, temple, and tomb by themselves for as long as either of them could remember.
That the attacks on them and their library had been growing more frequent and more violent as of late. I pledged to him that no longer would they have to do this alone, that from that day forward, I would assist them. I knew I could assist them better if I could get my hands on Balancekeeper, but I couldn't figure out how to do it. I kept reading the old book, but it had more to do with the Lance of the Void than it did with Balancekeeper.
The only way I could figure to get to the sword was to go through the temple, but I could not destroy the altar simply to get a sword, nor could I allow the violence necessary to break through a wall to occur in a library. I removed my sheath and placed it in front of the altar and I prayed to Gilean, keeping a constant vigil at the altar for a week defore I passed out.
When I awoke, I heard voices, three voices. I moved back into the library, away from the altar. I followed the voices as they grew in volume as though they were shouting. As I came around a corner I saw the Knight from the week before, he had returned with a fellow knight and know they were threatening the Librarian I had met that first day. They demanded he open the tomb and get them the sword or they would kill him.
None can open it but Gilean himself he informed them. This drove them into a rage and before I could reach them they both plunged their swords deep into his chest. Unable and unwilling to stop myself, I charged headlong into one of them, driving him into the wall and knocking the breath out of him. Before I could turn to the other, he had his sword raised and was alreasy swinging it at me.
I heard a loud clang and as I turned around, I saw the second Librarian standing there holding a quarterstaff, having just knocked out the second knight with it. The knight I tackled began to stir and I put my hand to my waist to get my sword. At that point I realised it wasn't there, I had left it on the altar!
I told the second librarian to run, to go with me back to the altar, but he didn't move, he just stood there, smiling sadly, as a blade was thrust through him, back to front, from the soldier I had knocked into the wall. I cried out, but there was nothing I could do. I ran back to the altar to get my sword, but as soon as I grabbed the hilt I knew something was different.
The Knight was close behind me so I didn't have time to look into it, I just grabbed the sheath, ripped it off and swung my sword in an arc that no trained swordwoman should ever have made, it shouldntve worked, I should have missed by a mile and been stabbed right then and there.
But it did work. The blade swung into the knight's neck, seperating his head from his shoulders. It was then that I saw it. The blade of this sword was not my own, this blade was crimson, this was Balancekeeper!
The knight the elderly Librarian had knocked out was stirring by the time I got back to where the old men had met their deaths. With a swift swing of my new sword I ended him. I laid the elderly Librarians to rest at the altar they had given their lives to protect and I began to make my way back to the town of Lemish, taking the little old book with me.
