I stand here, cowering as I kneel meekly before the god of the thieving
ones.  All my life I was considered lucky yet unlucky at the same time. 
Right when my life went right, something would always go wrong to change
everything back to the way it was.  I spent most of my life a gambler after
my parents death until I drained all of my inheritance.  I at first devoted
to Shinner, and the riches were finally more than enough to sustain me.  I
married a half-ling, fell in love, and even had children.  Where they are
now, I do not know.  At that time halflings were not liked by most anyway. 
I do hope they are safe.  My children I mean.  Where my wife is I do not
know.  It is my fault I guess.  We each exchanged harsh words the night she
ran from our mansion, swearing to all the dark gods and gods of the light
alike that I was no different than the rest.  Yes, it is true I did have a
mistress, but so help me, I did not expect her to find out, not so soon
anyway.  Afterwards I drank heavily.  I returned to my previous lifestyle. 
I guess even the might of shinner couldnt save me from the band of thieves
that robbed me one night.  Not simply robbed me, but followed me home.  A
rock-like being was waiting for me at the door of my prestigious house. 
Every time I attempted to enter, it would pick me up and throw me out of the
place -quite literally.  Having no home and no money, I quickly became a
beggar on the streets.  If only I could have gotten to my home to pawn a few
of my possessions once more just for a small taste of the exhilaration of
that sweet sweet gambling thrill.  Looking back on my death I now see the
error of my ways.  I now see that cursing shinner to the high heavens was a
bad idea.  Devoting to the god of the thieves was probably the worst step I
could make.  But here he is telling me I have served him well.  Its a pity
you had to die like that.  The good news is you were over do for a promotion
anyway I have done well by you my lord?  Yes, you have.  I am quite pleased.
I do apologize for the things I had to do to get you with me Elven, but in a
way, you saved me the trouble when you were thrown from that wagon into the
tree.  I am glad you are pleased my lord.  Lets see if we can make a deal
here.  You dont want to pay off your debt to me right now, right?  What can
you give me in return?  I have served you well my lord, all I ask is to
continue to do so however you see fit.  And continue you shall.  Well just
call this little favor I do for you a loan.  A loan that you shall pay back,
with interest.  Everything goes dark as a cold chill seeps into me.  Fear
grips my heart, mind, and nearly overpowers me.  Just when I think I can not
be any more frightened, I hear the most chilling words Ive ever heard.  They
do not ring to my ears as they did on the second plain, but instead are
piped through my head as if water through plumbing.  I need a spy, Elven,
one that will do as it is told.  One that remembers, thinks, and breathes,
but cannot be discovered.  I think your series of unfortunate events that
led you to me, most of which I caused, shall serve its purpose after all. 
Despite this minor set back, something can be worked out after all.  Be at
home with the water once more Elven.  See your mistress again.  Its the
cackle at the end that did it to me.  The last words I heard werent chilling
enough, he had to throw that cackle in there that grates against my nerve
endings.  The cackle that chilled me down to my very soul itself.  Gods have
mercy on me.  I should know by now, with the lord of the thieves, you dont
get something for nothing.  I have no doubt what he told me is true.  I
shall see my beloved once more.  I will feel the water of my homeland yet
again.  Possibly be embraced by my kind, but good gods, at wh at price?  
