Text
Consistency.
 
Atanate learned in the early stages of his training that consistency
was a good thing.  You had to be disciplined - memorize every syllable
and the correct pronounciation.  When you were skilled at your basic
magicks, you were to try and repeat the original formula over and over
again, never going off the edge, never making a mistake.  When you made
a mistake, you learned from it.  Maybe the spell was even stronger, and
you tried to repeat it.  Consistency was a way of life.
 
Atanate knew consistency.  Everyone knew what he was an expert at as
well.  There was one thing that Atanate could do that was better than
everyone else on the face of Krynn, and even the Gods out of it.  His
mastered art, one of a diamond clear consistency was that of failure.
Yes, failure.
 
Have you ever been too afraid to be right?  So sure that you were the
best, and could do what you set out to do with accuracy and efficiency?
Atanate thought so.  He was the best.  So good in fact, that he always
set himself up to fail.  Consistency.  He always failed, never made it.
 
Why?
 
Love.  Pain.  Life.  Magic.
When he fell in love, he soon fell out of love and experienced pain.
Overwhelmed by life and soon captivated by magic, Atanate unknowingly
started to plot in his head the perfect formula to keep him from ever
getting a broken heart again - do his hardest at wanting to be the best
but always take a step away as soon as it looks as if things might be
going his way.  It doesn't break his heart, it's the type of failure
and pain that he can easily get accustomed to.  Consistency.
Failure.
 
"{rI am sorry, Lunitari.{x"
 
The one reason Atanate did this was for a longer, better life.  But
again, as always, when you set yourself up to fail, you fail.
Atanate holds the jewel encrusted blade in his hand for a moment, what
a shame his life has been.  His goal was to become one of the Conclave
and now that he was on the right track, he had to step back.  Step away.
No more heartbreak.
 
Consistency.
 
No more.  The emotion surging through Atanate's veins as he holds the
dagger up high to end this consistent line of failure, is too much for
one to take in, through merely reading the texts of an old book.
How can this book be different than all of the others on the shelves.
Why, only because of its consistency.  Everyone knew what was going to
happen, and frankly nobody cares.  Especially Atanate.
 
"{rI do not deserve this magic.  I do not deserve this at all.{x"
 
Goodbye, Krynn.
-Atanate
