Subject The Return~
Text
After a long unexplained absence, Roivas searches for a ship, to return from his journey to Ergoth. Feeling almost drawn back to his home in Ansalon, he sails to the shores of Abanasinia. His searching driven only by hope, he walks, on foot, to the stronghold located east of Solace. Though no longer a Knight of Takhisis, he remains a High Priest, and knows he shall be welcomed to the temple within the stronghold -- even if for nothing but prayer.
 
Not quite as he expected, Roivas arrives at the stronghold to find it seemingly desolate, except for the guard and a few knights, which look distraught. One of them, an ogre, even steps forward, to speak. "Welcome, High Priest," the ogre says, respectfully. "Roivas, it is, correct?"
 
"Aye," replies Roivas, with a nod, although it seems to surprise him a bit. "I am only here to visit my Queen," he tells the men. The knights, seeming to ignore all else by the confirmation, continue speak again. This time, it is a human.
 
"You were once the Lord of Night, if I'm not mistaken?" he inquires, though obviously he was sure of the answer. 
 
"Many years ago," the High Priest recalls, speaking softly. "Does Lord Razel remain your leader?"
 
The knights look at each other with a bit of awkwardness, and the human says "Lord Razel is no longer Lord of Night, I'm afraid.. in fact, we no longer have one." This is the information that catches the interest of the man. Roivas ponders: could this be why I have been feeling drawn to this place?
 
It would be better to pray before assuming such a thing, he decides, and simply nods at the knights, turns on his heels, and begins to walk to the temple. "Wait, High Priest!" one of the knights calls, before he reaches the end of the hallway. "We have something to ask you." The ogre booms, saving the human from yelling again.
 
Roivas turns back around, and watches the knights jog up to him. "Will you take the place of our Lord, if only temporarily?"  the human inquires, and before he can reply, (seeing the expression on Roivas' face) the man continues, "the knighthood is in dire need of leadership. If for no one else, do it in the name of Takhisis."
 
That was enough for him, undoubtedly, it is Takhisis' will, he decides. Roivas, after praying, agrees to honor the knights' requests.
