Subject Istar Rising~
Text
The ruins of Mycaisa are precariously balanced upon the jagged edge of a black fissure. It cuts deep into the darkness of the sea, and as the dilapidated buildings succumb to age and neglect, they tumble one by one into the hungry abyss and are swallowed up.

The village was once the resting place of weary travelers and tradesmen, especially during the days when the gods were silent and Dimernesti feared voyaging by way of the Defiler's Breath. But, the volcanic vapors that now ooze from the gaping gash in the earth have poisoned the waters around Mycaisa, rendering it dark and silent. Now, elves shun the wretched ruins and whisper of its curse.

Osseus had passed near Mycaisa many times, and always the ash had burned his gills and spurred him away. But, as he navigated around its tainted waters on a night in mid-summer, he thought he heard voices singing in the distance. Pausing a moment, he listened.

Holding his breath and gathering his courage, the sea-elf flipperkicked into the stale, stagnant waters, unstirred for years. Drawing closer, the voices became more distinct, and he found himself braving the stinging waters till he arrived a very old building, teetering upon the doomed edge of the gaping pit.

The foolish elf's head reeled with toxins and his skin felt on fire, but he was transfixed by the tranquil voices, singing like sirens in the shadows. Their words were elven and honey.

"We sang for the Kingpriests in the golden times, and we sing for them still. But, we are soon lost." In a corner of the crooked room, something shimmered beneath a broken pillar of coral. It was a crown.

Wrapped in entwining patterns, the crown seemed wrought of solid gold. It was bejeweled in flawless rubies as red as blood. Without thinking, the sea-elf placed the crown upon his head, and in that instant the voices burst forth with startling intensity, ringing in his skull. The darkness had also grown so overwhelming that the low-hanging passage through which he had entered had now completely vanished. His eyes burned with acid, and unable to see, Osseus groped along the walls till he was free.

Cursing his curiosity, Osseus sped from the forgotten ruins until his muscles ached. The water became breathable, but the darkness of Mycaisa still surrounded him. He held out a webbed hand before his face, and a wave of despair fell over him. Osseus had lingered too long in the shunned city. The poison had blinded him.

"Though you cannot see," sang the elven voices, "we shall lead you."

Lights shone in Istar as the Great Temple glowed crimson, heralding its new Kingpriest. And from Istar now comes the strange message upon the lips of traders.

"The Crown of Power has been found. The Holy Empire is reborn."
~
