Subject The Escape~
Text
Rain.  The sky was dark, and rain fell from the skies.  The cold pattering
of raindrops was soothing to me.  It almost felt as if though the water
would wash away the anxiety I had felt.
 
I found myself dragging a boat across the sands of an island off of the
coast near Palanthas.  I bought it from a local fisherman for a decent
price.  I intended to go out for some sailing on the ocean.  I decided
that it was the best way to calm my nerves after what had happened to
me not to long ago.
 
You see, I had taken a great responcibility on my shoulders.  Call it the
will of the gods, or call it a knight's ambition to ensure that no harm
comes to innocents.  I call it a curse, now.  I'm not going to go into
much detail here, but there are things that I must safeguard.  Things that
by this curse must never leave my side.  Not too long ago, they had
almost done so, and a black plague would have spread once more.
 
I moved away from the shore, dragging the boat with me and going waist
deep into the water.  I then climbed into the wooden vessel as best I
could without getting much water in it.  I picked up the oars inside
and began to row out to sea, closing my eyes and letting my heart take
me where it would.
 
Hours passed.  The sun set over the horizon and the moon had raised well
into the sky.  The rain still lightly poured, giving me a strange sense
of security.  I finally opened my eyes to take a look around.  From any
direction I stared to, all I could see was ocean.  This would be perfect
for me.
 
I removed a backpack from my shoulders and placed it infront of me.  I
began to search through the enchanted backpack, whose size was a lot
larger on the inside then it was on the outside.  I pulled from within
it three things; a halberd, a sword, and some rope.  I then closed the
backpack and placed it on my shoulders, tightening it so it would stay
close.
 
I took the halberd in my left hand and the rope in my right.  I began
to tie the item firmly to me, using several knots and looping the rope
around my hand several times.  Once I felt confident in the stability
of the rope, I picked up the sword.  I could lightly see my reflection
in the clean blade from what little light there was.  The importance
of these two things was so grave, it almost seemed unreal to me.  How
stupid it was that such things boiled things down to this.
 
I slowly stood up to the best of my ability, trying not to cause the
boat to tip over.  Once I had found my balance, I looked up at the dark
night sky.  I closed my eyes and allowed the water to hit my face.  Rain.
I loved the rain.  Rain was always my favorite part of the natural world.
 
I knew it had to be done.  I wispered, "Est Sularas oth Mithas," to the
night sky.  Knowing my duty, I punctured the sword through my chest.  I
almost immediatly felt the metallic tang of blood in my mouth.  I smiled.
I remembered one time telling a young boy looking to be a knight that I
had been looking for an escape as a knight for a long time.  Of course then,
I was joking.  I could never predict that something so important would boil
it down to this.
 
I felt my body fall from the boat and crash into the water.  The weight of
my armor began to drag me down into the clutches of the ocean.  I could
still hear the rain pattering on the surface of the water for a while.
Soon enough, however, there was nothing.  Conciousness faded.  My mind
slipped away.  I could only guess that soon after my soul passed on; that,
or it was bound eternally to protect the weapons that had been so dangerous
to the bottom of the sea.  Whatever works, I suppose.  I never did like
endings like this.  Figures that would be mine.
 
Executor Gulgor Arestanadok
Marquis of the Auxiliary
~
