Text
The trees of the forest rustle in the gentle wind, the leaves falling all around.  The small creatures of the forest scamper upon the forest floor, avoiding the kagonesti that slowy strolls though the dense forest.
"{YWear is that damn place, all I see are trees.{x"
His eyes dart back and forth, from tree to tree, bush to bush. He continues to examine everything, as if he is searching for something. His sword clangs inside it's sheath with every step. The bard continues to survey the land, his bright blue eyes roaming over every bit of the forest he can see. His eyes stop moving, focused on something, He pick up the pace and runs towards the object.
"{YIs this really it?{x"
He runs over to the area of focus and stops suddenly, a look of achievment on his face.
"{YI think I finally found it. The entrance into my family's tomb.{x"
The bard looks up to see a thick branch hanging overhead, and jumps up to grab it. He swings his body back and forth and begins to swing on the branch. He lets go of the branch tossing himself over the thick brush and almost face first into a large boulder. A faint, cool breeze escapes the boulder, as if there is an entrance behind it. Linx attempts to push the boulder oput of the way, but fails to even budge the tramendously heavy object.
"{YHoly shit, this thing is heavy.{x"
He begins to rumage through his pack, hoping to find something useful. He pulls out a thick peice of rope.
"{YThis might work...{x" 
He ties the rope around the boulder, and tosses the other end over a thick branch. He pulls on the rope, but the boulder doesn't budge. He continues to pull on the rope, but the branch snaps, and falls down on the bard. He lets out a small sigh and examines the boulder to find that there is some kind of inscription carved into it.
"{DOnly those who have orven themselves to the family may enter this sacred tomb.{x"
Linx studies the inscription carefully, and places his hand on the boulder.
"{YSo, I have proven myself, so why can I not still move this damn thing?{x"
Linx stands up and with a slight shrug begins to push on the boulder as hard as he can. His face going bloodshot, and his feet digging into the ground, the boulder finally budges. It slowly creeps out of the way, Linx's blood vessels seemingly about to explode in his face. 
"{YBy...the gods....{x"
Linx stops pushing the boulder and falls to the ground, exausted. He looks up at the boulder and looks past into the tight squeeze of an opning.
"{YI should be able to fit through there.{x"
Linx takes a deep breath and climbs to his feet. He slowly stumbles into the gap, obviously exausted, and almost falls flat to his face.
"{YI think I might have to take a nap, I can't move my arms...{x" 
His words fall short as he falls asleep. 
 
Linx awakes to the sound of the trees flailing back and forth in the wind. He peek outside the entrance to see that the sky is black and a heavy rain falls from the clouds. Lighting flashes in the sky and the thunder echoes loudly through the small tomb. Linx gathers himself and climbs to his feet. He looks around and begins to walk deeper into the tomb. His eyes look around at the many caskets that line the halls.
"{YI'm curious as to how long my family has actually been around, and I am curious as to who the first person was that started us.{x"
Linx continues to walk, down the never ending hall of the tomb. The cobblestones at his feet worn away form hundreds years of erosion and decay. A light seems to glowe faintly frmo the end of the hall, and the bard picks up his pace and begins to run towards the light. His sword clangs at his side as he comes to a quick stop at the end of the hallway, the door in front of him left slighty ajar. He slowly opens the door and peeks inside to see a tall sarcophagus, made from gold.
 Hanging at it's side is a small golden harp. Linx slowly walks over to the wall and picks the harp off the wall, only to see an inscription carved into the wall;
"{DBrave young music lover, protect what you hold close, and use the power if this instrument to help guide you in your journies. Bring the harp back, and rest it upon the pedastal when the time comes for you to lay in your eternal resting place.{x"
Linx holds the harp in his hands and lightly strums the string, a soothing hum begins to eminate from the harp, and echo through the room. He lowers the harp, turns and walks out the door only to return back to the library he holds close.  
