Subject The Baker's Last Dozen~
Text
The evening {Ysun{  set gently over the horizon. The last rays of light retreating from the winding rows of buildings that make up the great city of Palanthas. The bakery was just emptying of its final customers of the day. Bags filled with pot pies and loaves of bread being brought home to fill the bellies of waiting families.
The Baker milled about performing his final chores of the day: cleaning the oven, scrubbing the granite countertops, and emptying the display case of its stale contents. The Baker pauses and glances worriedly at the door as the last patron exits. Alone. The part of the day he dreaded most. It hasn't always been this way he remembered.
 Only a month before he thanked Paladine when the day of work was concluded. But since the day the young man approached him about the offer for usage of a spare storage cellar, things had changed. A simple deal. Fifty steel a week and you can come and go as you please. There is only an entrance in the back, so it wouldn't even disturb his place of business.
Easy money. He let out a chuckle at the thought. Then his mind snapped back to the moment he walked back to the cellar entrance. The meeting he interrupted. The things he shouldn't have seen. "I know to much..." He whispered to himself. Losing his concentration he dropped a hard dinner roll off of a tray. It falls to the floor with a thud and rolls beneath the counter coming to rest under the crawlspace.
Cursing under his breath he debates leaving it. Then thinks of the rats thanking him for the feast he left them and reconsiders. The Baker, a very portly man, squats down to his hands and knees to accomodate the cramped space and begins squeezing forward. The roll came to rest at the very back of the enclosure. His outstretched hand still out of reach, he inches forward to grasp the baked good.
Suddenly the silence of the room is broken. The bells affixed above the entrance that alert him that customers have arrived when he is tending the oven or, on a slow day, taking a nap ring loudly. The Baker freezes up in fear and remains motionless, deafened by the pounding pulse of blood in his head. "I'm sorry we're closed!" the Baker managed to yell.
Even muffled from underneath the counter, the terror in his voice was clearly audible. No answer. The Baker's mind was racing and sweat poured from every pore.He began slowly inching backwards to free himself from the cramped prison. The sound of footsteps made him freeze again. But these were not steps from feet. More like steps from a horse. And from the sounds of the floorboards creaking, a very large one. With his last ounce of strength the Baker pushed back hard.
Flinging himself free and falling onto his back into the gaze of two figures. "Please! I know nothing!" the Baker stammered. "From your death. We profit." The voice was harmonic almost. That night the rats thanked the baker for the feast he left them.
~
