A woman sat in the back courner of a dark jail cell somewhere
in Palanthas.  Lucky enough to have the cell to herself, she
stares into the quiet darkness, footsteps of guards patroling
the only thing reminding her she wasen't alone.
 
Smoke rised lightly from a blunt in her right hand, a small
comfort she was lucky enough to sneak in.  'Good thing they
don't check -everywhere-,' the woman thought to herself.  She
raised the blunt up to her mouth and took a long drag from
it, coughing lightly so as not to arouse any attention from
the guards.
 
Ever since she got hooked to the precious green herb, she
hasen't had an...incident for months.  The influence of the
drug has made her do some stupid shit recently, but at least...
at least it was better then the blackouts.  Better then
being in pain, and being scared.  Better then waking up in
some random alley or in the forests to find that she had been
covered in blood, from events beyond her to recall.
 
'What's wrong with me?  I hate this...'  She raised the blunt
to her mouth, taking another drag from it, hoping that the high
of the drug would continue to do its job, and at least keep her
from losing herself again.  Even though anything was better then
that, she sat in the jail cell, miserable at what she let her
life crumble into.
 
Was she clinically insane?  Perhaps.  She could still recall the
days of her childhood, being raised on a facility for being "mad."
She had overheard the priests there, talking about their theories
of her being possessed.  The thought made her shiver, and forced
her to take another drag off of the blunt.
 
She couldn't blame her actions entirely on the blunts she so craved
to keep the blackouts from happening.  She knew that on some strange
and twisted reason, she liked being locked up, as long as it was
only for a while.  It made her feel safe, despite the lack of comforts
and the cold treatment of the guards.  Was it the fact that she
knew being locked up, she couldn't do anything she would regret?
Or, was it because there were others here that had the same kind of
problems on their plate.  After all, misery loves company.
 
She took one last drag and hid the smoked-out blunt under a loose
rock.  "All out," she said.
 
She rolled over in her courner and went to sleep to the sound
of patrolling guards.
