library consumed his free time, while a strict regime of work and practice
of various skills, assigned by his parents, covered the rest.  When Fyrah
was about the age of 10, his house was attacked by a group of thieves.  A
rough bunch, dust-covered faces and an eye for wealth in all of them.  The
only one that stood out being, what was assumed as, their leader.  A brute
of a man, towering above the average sized thieves, carrying a large gelatin
shaped axe on his back.  When they had shown up, Fyrah's parents only had
enough time to hide him under a loose floor board.  Looking up through the
cracks, Fyrah gazed upon the threatening and questioni ng of his parents,
and later their execution by the brute.  Their decapitated heads rolled
along the floor, his mothers head stopping at an angle above the crack Fyrah
looked through, her eyes set on him.  The graphic things he saw that day
never left him, only fueling a want for revenge deep inside him.  Wishing
them all the pain he could bring, Fyrah researched magic from the many books
in his library he didnt pay attention to before.  One school of magic caught
his eye particularly, illusion, how it manipulated the mind and senses, and
when mastered could torture someone from the inside out.  Fyrah had found a
