Going about his daily duties, searching for renegades and acts that violate the precepts of Good, he sat atop a tower looking into his scrying bowl. While projecting his vision through a random dark alley way between rows of houses, he catches out of the corner of his eyes a break in. A rather small group of hooligans, causing mischief most likely.
 
Appalled by the petty acts of this group, he stands immediately, summoning a gate and vanishing into it. As he steps out of it, he looks around at the small house he had arrived at, the group of hooligans in front of him, having obviously grabbed their attention. On the floor lied a man, dressed in commoner clothing, a sword protruding from his back. Beside him, a woman with an open throat, still chocking on her own blood.
 
Flashbacks of his own parents deaths rang through Fyrah's mind. The petty hooligans charged him out of fear, only to have their weapons make a soft 'ding' sound as they bounced off Fyrah's Shield spell he had up. Looking forward, not noticing the hooligans at all, Fyrah stands in a daze as memories he hadnt looked back on in years tortured his mind. 
 
Eyes darting about the room, at the death of this common man and woman, noting every small detail that was alike with his own parents cruel end, Fyrah's pulse begins to rise and anger resonates through his body. The vengeance he once had let go of had come back, his mind confusing the situation with his own.
 
Some time had passed before he had ever left that small house, leaving behind only bodies. It was only moments before he put the pieces together, realizing what he had done. Immediately taking refuge in a library near Palanthas, owned by a friend, he began to seek answers in the books around him, but to no avail. 
 
With time he accepted his actions. He accepted the fact that theres both evil, and good. His old admissions' of protecting the 'innocent' seemed so juvenile to him, so absurd. The darkness in his heart, as there is in all others, was present just as much as the light. 
 
Fyrah came to the conclusion that they were both needed. As long as there was Good, Evil would arise to fight it, and vice versa, and that was the order of things. Without that order and constant movement, Krynn would stand still and progress.
 
With this new mindset, he sets out to the towers of the conclave. Having already discarded the white robes he so proudly wore not to long ago, he receives a set of fine red robes.
