((Just what happens when someone opens it and reads it? Silvaria has become
Ordermaster Darkahn Kiralv's ambassador to the Foresters. She is within Wayreth,
having a brief meeting with him, when he is summoned away from the Black
Tower by a keening wail from elsewhere in Wayreth. As he leaves his chambers to
investigate, the following takes place.))

Silvaria sits on the hearth for a while before her mood changes to that of
intense curiosity. She stands and begins to wander around the shelves of the
room, peering at the spines of the aged books. The thought nags the back of
her mind, but she doesn't consider the journal until she comes to stand
before the desk. She stands over it, staring at it, something holding her back
while something else tells her to open it.

Silvaria peers over her shoulder and glances around the room, not sure why
she feels like someone could be watching when she had heard him lock the door
behind him. Once she is confident no one is there, however, she turns her full
attention to the journal and, after hesitating only to take a deep breath,
takes the cover in one hand and opens to the first page.

As she does so, she notices immediately that the stains are not black, but red.
In fact, the putrid stench of blood remains; indeed, the writing looks to
remain wet to the touch, as fresh as it had been when it was first put on
the page. Without warning, she hears what sounds like a chorus of whispers;
what starts as one voice becomes dozens, and dozens become hundreds, and
hundreds become thousands. Their chorus becomes louder, almost deafeningly so.

Silvaria feels the urge to cover her ears to the strange noise, but she can't
take her eyes away from the spidery handwriting etched in bloodred. She
moves her hand toward it, and lays a finger lightly upon the page. The
melody ceases.

The blood is bone-chillingly cold, forcing her to jerk back from the touch.
As she does, she can't help but take a look at her finger, to check it
for damage. The blood runs from her finger, down to her palm, to her arm,
and it continues to spread. In fact, it seems to consume her arm, moving
across her entire body like a liquid plague, slowly creeping up her neck.

A gasp, then a strangled cry escapes Silvaria, cut off by the cold bloodcurse.
She shivers uncontrollably, as the curse makes its way through her body,
falls to her knees and curls up while she still has feeling in her back
and stomach. Soon, though, she can barely feel her chest enough to draw
breath. She can barely even think, to berate herself for her curiosity.

The blood finally finds its way to her face, consuming the entirety of
her head and even delving into her mouth -- an unnatural, internal cold
overtaking her. The blood begins to glow and, before long, like a torrent or
a mealstrom, the book consumes the blood once more; drawing her with it.


