chase of the night. It is still too early for the morning
birds to sing their songs, and much of the Forester Temple
remains asleep in their hammocks and on their nests of soft
foliage.
 
There remains at least one awake -- though she does not lie
within the Temple proper. Beyond the familiar haven of Golametti's
hut grows a large tree with thick, low-lying branches. A pale
figure can be seen nestled betwixt two limbs, her odd eyes gazing
out over the rest of the Temple. Pale, chromatic light glimmers along
the pathways, emitted by small fungi that glow under the light of
the Moons. Silvaria watches them twinkle and wink out as daylight
creeps over the forest.
 
Her thoughts are far from the small mushrooms, though a part of her
does enjoy the sight of them. Sleep has eluded her this night because
her mind ruthlessly plays over haunting memories and worriesome
thoughts.
 
As new leader of the Foresters -- the third in the time of a
year -- she has struggled to find her place among these peaceful
people. Where they had been content to call her one of their own
before, something feels amiss now. Regardless of attempts to bring
herself closer to them, there is distrust -- she can feel it.
 
Her application to take the position of Keeper had been stiff,
and when she looks back upon it, she feels doubt and uncertainty.
She wonders to herself, now, if writing an application had been
the right way to approach the position. There is muted talk of
the leader before her, whose word she had hastily dismissed. She
hadn't known Anavrin, and she does not know his daughter, to whom
he had left leadership in his resignation. Regardless, to so readily
brush aside his wishes while he lay upon his deathbed... The guilt
weighs upon her, and she hasn't the slightest idea of what to do
about it.
 
Of course, the circumstances surrounding her disappearance -- and
the increased activity of mages in the Temple following her
return from Kalaman -- only fuel the distress. The memory of
Theriss razing the nearby forests is fresh for many of the
inhabitants, and they speak of the damage and casualties as though
it had happened just the day before. She wonders if they think
she will welcome those who wish them harm, when that is the
farthest from her intention.
 
Still, she was gone for weeks at a time, during a time when she
had promised that she would be dedicated to helping them.
And, each time, it had followed the appearance of a Conclavian mage
within the Temple. Not to mention the "medicine" that she had
been so unwittingly welcome to speak of, before...
 
'{CI ought to have taken this slower,{X' she murmurs to herself
as the birds in the trees around her begin to wake and sing,
rousing the Foresters below in turn. '{CI should have considered
these things closer, done more research, spent more time, been
more respectful...{X' Silvaria sighs deeply. Her eyelids are
heavy with exhaustion, but she moves methodically to stretch
her cramped muscles.
 
A careful movement slips her safely from the branches of the tree
to the ground, and once there, she takes a long drink from her
runed elixir. A soft sound makes her look up suddenly, and as she
sees Golametti standing there, she drops the elixir to her side
and presses it closely to her leg, out of sight.

'{CGood morning, Golametti,{X' Silvaria says quietly.

'{y...Yes, and to you,{x' the elderly elf replies hesitantly. He
