Darkness.  This was the eternal constant within the ocean depths. 
Certainly, there were often times where some sort of bioluminescence shown
through -- the glowing orbs of undersea life trying to entice creatures
which had wondered too low of an anglerfish, or the star-like jellyfish
which lit up the waters as she imagined the night sky did.  No other light
found its way, however.  Xinaesa had little idea what she looked like.  She
knew that she was one of the most changed of the Mahkwahb, with little
evidence that "dolphin" blood had ever been in her ancestry.  Pallid skin

the color of the sea sand, hair as dark as the deepest waters, and eyes that
shimmered crimson like the scales of a sea serpent.  But she had never seen
her reflection at her home -- she had to rely on the appearance of her
hands, and how others spotted her.  Then again, she did not have much an
idea of what others looked like either; their scent and the sight of their
heat was all she had to go by.  Her tribe was little known -- whispers,
rumors.  They had long forsook the creature forms of their ancestors,
forsook their gods, forsook Habbakuk.  They embraced Zurra -- Zeboim, almost

universally.  She was the true master of the seas, and they could feel it in
their blood when they took their shark forms more than any other time.  The
dead of their tribe were never wasted, of course.  Their bodies were
typically abandoned, for they knew that rest was finite, though the hunger
was endless.  Xinaesa had seen for herself her elder sister return, still
with a spear through her bleeding heart, touched by Undeath.  Her sister had
been a great hunter -- the pride of her family.  But there were taboos even
the Mahkwahb held, and in Xinaesa's mind, she had violated them.  To mock

Zeboim was blasphemy.  The gift of Eternal Hunger was not one her sister
planned to wait for.  She wanted the power then and now, and she embraced a
foreign god -- learning from a tome dropped from the land-dwelling peoples
of "Chemosh."  Xinaesa had hoped to end her sister's blasphemies then and
there.  Instead, she found her coming back to life, just the same -- though
by whose touch she did not know.  And now, she was fleeing -- for she had
violated another one taboo herself by killing her only sibling.  Fratricide.
For the first time in her as of then short life, she felt something akin to
sorrow.  Not so much as the loss of her sister, but the loss of her home.  
 
So she swam -- up to the verboten surface.
~
