She swam -- upwards.  Her shark form allowed her to quickly rend the
flesh of prey, and her speed was immense -- more than it would have been in
an elven form.  Either form, of course, would have been an ample target for
the other races which despised both her abyssal family and the sharks of the
oceans.  The growing light from above impeded her progress.  Her eyes could
not adjust, as much as she wanted to.  She was now truly an outcast, and
there was no going back.  Part of her wanted to take in this newfound world,
the new sights and sounds -- and tastes.  The other part loathed every

moment, however.  The surface was getting closer, now.  She had managed to
avoid her own predators -- and there was something in her that called her
on, whether inspiration or curiosity.  She stopped, however, struggling
against something as the sight of the moons reflected against the water. 
She morphed back into her elven body, finding herself trapped within a
fishing net.  Scarlet eyes peered about, noting the amount of lesser sea
creatures that were stuck with her, sloshing about in their desperate
struggles for freedom.  The girl let out a scream underwater, trying to

unbind herself -- but she had no weapons to cut free, no tools to utilize. 
Hours passed like this; much like the fish about her, she made a desperate
attempt for freedom, her screams interlaced with prayers to Zeboim spoken
out loud.  She thought for a moment they had been answered as she felt the
net tug.  The sun's rays blinded her, however, and as she was withdrawn from
the water, words came in tongues she did not know -- along with the hard

impact against the wooden surface of the ship.  Her twisted body was almost
crushed by the weight of the fish which spilled onto her.  The impact alone
had hurt, and the bizarre feeling of being out of the water was maddening. 
She had never used her lungs before -- and in desperate sputters the gills
at the sides of her neck tried at first to take in air.  
 
The stench, however, gave her some orientation. It was a wooden ship,
and she was the only elf -- and the only female, judging by the pheromones
she felt raging.
